New study

Published in: Problem Paradise no. 105 (vol.27), January-March 2024.

File: Neuenschwander-2024-ProblemParadise105.pgn

=0002.02c8e8 (1949). Correction

Date: 2024, April 4

File: Zakhodyakin1949.pgn

Study no. 71 (Table 1 in beatochess-01)

Adding a black pawn on e6 correct the study. However, there are two interesting features which do not change the content of the study. First, the white king could as well be on c6. Second, the black pawn could be on g3. The latter allows the black knight to be on b4 rather than b8, which makes the first move even more suprising. The correction uses these findings.

GBR: =0002.02c8e8 FEN: 1NK1k2N/4p3/8/8/8/4p3/8/8 w - - 0 1

Shakhmaty v SSSR/1. U2: Beasley=J HHdbIII 44615 3-2-2002. 1. Na6! e2 2. Nc7+ Kf8 3. Ne6+ (3. Ng6+! cook JB ) 3 Kg8 4. Nf7! e1=Q (4 Kxf7 5. Ng5+) 5. Nfg5! Qd2 eg 6. Kc7 Qd5 7. Kb6 Qc4 8. Kb7 1/2-1/2.

GBR: =0002.03c6e8 FEN: 4k2N/4p3/2K1p3/8/1N6/6p1/8/8 w - - 0 1

correction: Neuenschwander=B beatochess 04/04/2024. 1. Na6! g2 2. Nc7+ Kf8 (2 Kd8 3. Nxe6+ Kc8 4. Ng6 g1=Q 5. Nxe7+ =) 3. Nxe6+ Kg8 4. Nf7! g1=Q 5. Nfg5 1/2-1/2.

+3200.33g1h4 (1967). Version

Date: 2024, April 7

File: Zakhodyakin1967.pgn

Study no. 107 (Table 1 in beatochess-01)

The RRvsQ ending seems difficult to fix: the white rooks are simply to strong given the bad position of the black king. In addition to the cook on move 1, there is also the alternative win 4.Rg1 in the main line.

The version shows the theme (luring the black queen to g7 and trapping it) with a white knight and rook.
